You can use JavaScript to extract the file name and extension from a URL by using regular expressions. Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to achieve this:

```javascript
function getFileNameAndExtension(url) {
    var match = url.match(/\/([^\/?#]+)[^\/]*$/);
    if (match) {
        var fileNameWithExtension = match[1];
        var index = fileNameWithExtension.lastIndexOf(".");
        if (index !== -1) {
            var fileName = fileNameWithExtension.substring(0, index);
            var extension = fileNameWithExtension.substring(index + 1).toUpperCase();
            return { fileName: fileName, extension: extension };
        }
    }

    return null;
}

var url = 'https://d.dam.test.com/a/UyGSAon/test_how_to-V1.pdf?rc=10';
var result = getFileNameAndExtension(url);

if (result) {
    console.log('File Name: ' + result.fileName);
    console.log('Extension: ' + result.extension);
} else {
    console.log('Invalid URL format');
}
```

In this code snippet, the `getFileNameAndExtension` function takes a URL as input and uses a regular expression to extract the file name and extension from the URL. It then returns an object containing the extracted file name and extension.

When you run this code with the provided URL (https://d.dam.test.com/a/UyGSAon/test_how_to-V1.pdf?rc=10), it should output:

```
File Name: test_how_to-V1
Extension: PDF
```

